Today we‚Äôre celebrating trees‚Äîit‚Äôs Arbor Day. I made this image of a grove of buttressed jungle trees festooned with other plants to express the interdependence of life inside a rainforest in Belize. Tree trunks carry nutrients between the forest floor and the canopy. Fallen leaves and other organic debris are broken down by organisms in the soil, then their nutrients are absorbed by tree roots and carried back up to the canopy with remarkable swiftness. In a tropical rainforest, from the moment a leaf falls to earth to the time it is decomposed can take as little as three weeks. We‚Äôre all dependent on trees‚Äîwhat they exhale, we inhale. We are linked together in the cycle of life.

@thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeotravel @natgeocreative #ArborDay #RainForest #Trees #Nature #NaturePhotography #Beauty

I share this image in celebration of World Penguin Day! In late winter in Antarctica, the first emperor penguin chicks are exposed to the world. Parents cradle them on their feet to keep them warm and off the sea ice. It takes heroic parenting skills to raise a chick in this brutally cold environment where temperatures can drop to 40 degrees below zero with winds of more than 100 miles per hour. I spent a month camped on the sea ice near an emperor penguin colony to document how the chicks grow up. Browse through my feed for more images and stories about these remarkable birds.

@thephotosociety @natgeotravel @natgeocreative #Penguin #Nature #EmperorPenguin #Antarctica #Chick #Parent #Nurture #Love #WorldPenguinDay #naturephotography

I share this image in celebration of Earth Day. One day, after overnight rain had drenched California‚Äôs Big Sur coast, sunlight and morning clouds blended land, sea, and air together, enabling me to capture this landscape as a dynamic visualization of a living Earth. The first Earth Day in 1970 marks the birth of the modern environmental movement. It‚Äôs more important now than ever. We all need to stay engaged, and the best place to start is in our local communities. That‚Äôs where everything begins.

Photo by @FransLanting My home along the coast of California is situated in prime cougar habitat, and for a number of years I‚Äôve deployed camera traps to document this elusive cat. One of my favorite locations is an overgrown trail that comes out of a steep wooded canyon and passes right next to our land. One morning a wary male passed by an old oak tree festooned with lichen. The look in his eye epitomizes the character of this cat. Cougars were nearly wiped out along the coast of California near Santa Cruz where I live, but since they were given protection in 1990, they‚Äôve rebounded. They now occur even at the edges of towns and cities, but they are very good at avoiding people. The comeback of cougars in California is a success story, and it shows what can happen if we‚Äôre tolerant of apex predators and if we‚Äôre protecting enough wild land where they can survive. Stay tuned for more images that celebrate wild California.

It‚Äôs spring in California and the poppies are blooming‚Äîand blowing in the wind. This is a glorious season along the coast, especially after the welcome winter rains we‚Äôve had this year. From the air the land is emerald green right now. This is also the time of year when we host photography workshops at our studio in Santa Cruz at the edge of Monterey Bay, where I‚Äôve lived for more than 30 years. We organize field trips to some of my favorite places and help unleash everyone‚Äôs creativity. It‚Äôs rewarding to me to see how I can make a difference in how other people see and interpret the world with their cameras. Stay tuned for more images from the Monterey Bay.

Emperor penguins raise their young on the sea ice surrounding Antarctica where there is no vegetation or rocks with which they could build nests. When the young are just born, parents brood them on their feet. But a few weeks later the chicks start wandering around on their own. I came across this one, maybe a month old, at the edge of a colony, where it was awaiting the return of its parents. Without a nest site to come back to, emperor penguins and their offspring have evolved an amazing ability to find each other by sound. Imagine the cacophony of parents and chicks calling each other. It‚Äôs remarkable that this all works out. Truly a wonder of nature! Stay tuned for more amazing tales from the Southern Ocean.

@thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeotravel @natgeocreative #penguins #nature #explore #wildlifephotography #amazing #cute #baby #alone #wildlifeplanet #wildlifeonearth

It‚Äôs always rush hour on the beaches of South Georgia Island where awesome numbers of king penguins are going into the water to start fishing offshore. It‚Äôs a testimonial to the richness of this Southern Ocean ecosystem and the importance of this island at the edge of Antarctica as a sanctuary for marine life. Check my posts @FransLanting to learn more about the amazing life history of king penguins on this spectacular island.

@thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeotravel @natgeocreative #wildlifephotography #nature #naturelovers #wild #rushhour #amazing #awesome #picoftheday #ocean #penguins #wildlifeplanet #earthfocus #wildlife #earthtodolist

Young albatrosses take many months to mature before they‚Äôre ready to take flight and head off to sea. These black-browed albatross chicks have a long way to go before they can lift their wings and become the supreme flyers sailors have admired for centuries. They‚Äôre all sitting on mud nests built by their parents, who are searching the open ocean for squid to take back to their downy offspring in the Falkland Islands. I love albatrosses! To me they are among the most amazing creatures on the planet. I never get tired of watching them and photographing them.

Photo by @NASA  Celebrate Earth Hour! Turn off your lights for one hour at 8:30 pm, your local time, on Saturday March 25, to show solidarity with Planet Earth and demonstrate our global commitment to fighting climate change. Landmarks all over the world will go dark including the Empire State Building, the Eiffel Tower, Big Ben, the Sydney Opera House, and the Las Vegas Strip. This year marks the 10th anniversary of Earth Hour, an initiative that was first organized by the World Wildlife Fund in Australia and has grown into a worldwide movement. Join in! We can all be heroes for our planet. This image is the perfect symbol for island Earth, our home.

Brown chicks are mixed with adults ready to start a next breeding cycle. Check my feed @FransLanting for more amazing images and stories of this Antarctic wildlife spectacle.

@thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeocreative @natgeotravel #Penguins #Nature #Awesome #picoftheday #Wild

This male elephant seal is exhausted. He‚Äôs lost a lot of his body weight after weeks of fighting and fasting on a beach on South Georgia Island in the Antarctic. If you‚Äôre born as a male elephant seal you‚Äôre in for a life of all or nothing. Males weigh up to 4,000 pounds; they bulk out like prizefighters to gain a physical advantage over rivals who fight each other intensely to take control over beaches where females haul out. A handful of males get access to most of the females; all the other males are out of luck. Pups are born a year later on the same beach where they‚Äôre conceived. Check my previous posts to see how adorable the pups look during their first two months. After that they turn into super-size seals. Stay tuned for more tales from South Georgia, the island of superlatives.

@thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeocreative @natgeotravel #sleep #worn out #aggression #competition #nature #photooftheday #wildlife #naturelovers

Eyes full of innocence light up the face of this elephant seal pup which is less than two months old. Yet it‚Äôs already been weaned by its mother, who nourished it for a month with milk that is one of the highest in fat content of any animal on earth, and now it‚Äôs languishing on the shores of South Georgia before it takes a plunge into the cold waters of the Southern Ocean. Elephant seals dive deeper than almost any other marine mammal; some of them go farther down than 7000 feet. It takes more than big eyes to survive down there. Watch out, young seal! Stay tuned for more stories about seals and other wonders from South Georgia, the island at the end of the world.

You don't need a fancy camera to take great photos of your clients. Your application should be so on-point that no matter what camera you use, whether it's an iPhone or a DSLR - it should look pretty much the same. One thing that helps though is taking photos in good lighting. Whether that's in front of a window or ring light (natural light is always best), it's basically key to good photos. I always use a flash, as I find that helps capture the skin and glow perfectly. Work on your application, take your time to perfect it, there's no rush. Don't rely on smoothing filters. Your clients want to see what your real work looks like, not the work of a filter. 
This being said (before I get attacked), I sometimes like to enhance my own photos of myself with filters - but never my clients photos! For those who ask, the camera I use for my photos is the Sony Alpha a600. I also use my iPhone 7. üì∏ #heidimakeupartist

Oh ya, menu-menu lain di sini harganya murah juga lho. Satu porsi rata-rata harganya sekitar Rp 20.000 sampai Rp 30.000-an aja!

Menu rumahan kaya tumis jamur, bala-bala, oseng sayur ada semua di sini. Malah kadang ada menu yang jarang dimasak di rumah Mang Mimin juga lho kaya usus ayam karamel. Teksturnya renyah dan manisnya pas! Enak banget buat dimakan bareng nasi. Harga menu di sini mulai Rp 10.000 sampai Rp 20.000-an. Sama-sama kaya cabang yang lain, air putih di sini free flow!

VERDICT: Kalau ada yang hipster, semuanya pasti berbondong-bondong buat coba.

Biasanya Mang Mimin paling suka cari yang manis-manis kalau lagi bete. Biar nggak bete lagi, Mang Mimin kayanya bakal ke @warunk_upnormal buat nyobain menu sweet temptations yang ada di sana!

Kalau ke rumah makan Padang, Mang Mimin sih favoritnya makan Rendang. Tapi kata temen Mang Mimin ada juga lho menu daging selain rendang yang nggak kalah enak namanya dendeng batokok. Bentar, kayanya kalau yang satu ini Mang Mimin baru denger deh. Belinya dimana ya?

Ternyata dendeng batokok ini adanya di @rmsarumpun yang baru aja buka. Harga menu ala carte di sini lumayan murah lho! Satunya mulai dari Rp 8.000 sampai Rp 14.000 aja. Kalau mau pesen nasi plus rendang batokok atau rendang jadinya Rp 17.000.

Daging Dendeng Batokoknya empuk. Walaupun berlimpah cabe, tapi rasanya nggak terlalu pedes. Mang Mimin juga sempet icip Rendangnya. Bumbu rempah khas rendangnya kuat banget tapi nggak pedes juga. Kalau dateng ke sininya rada pagian, kamu juga bisa lho nyobain menu sarapan khas Padang salah satunya Soto Padang. Seporsi cuma Rp 17.000 aja!

VERDICT: Ternyata ada yang nggak kalah nendang dari rendang.

Buat ngeimbangin hobi makan Mang Mimin, kayanya makan sehat aja belum cukup deh. Apalagi lemak-lemak kayanya susah banget pergi kalau udah masuk ke badan. Mang Mimin disaranin sama Ms Mimin buat minum Slim Tea Tox dari @thegreentea_. Katanya kalau minum ini sebulan bisa turun 2 sampai 10 kilo lho!

1 box Slim Tea Tox @thegreentea_ ini isinya ada 20 kantong teh. Kalau liat di box-nya sih Slim Tea Tox ini bagus buat ngilangin lemak, ngecilin perut, memperlancar BAB dan menurunkan kadar kolestrol. Cara minumnya kamu tinggal seduh aja 2 kantong teh @thegreentea_ ke dalam air panas 200ml - 300ml terus diemin deh 15 sampai 20 menit. Buat pemula kaya Mang Mimin, efeknya bisa kerasa 6 sampai 12 jam setelahnya.

Harga 1 box-nya Rp 60.000. Kamu juga bisa langsung beli 4 box seharga Rp 200.000 yang bisa dipake buat 1 bulan. Kalau mau pesen langsung aja ya hubungin WA: 087821840805, Line: @thegreentea (pake '@') atau BBM: D65623C7.

@shuffle.id Boardgame Library
Jl. Cijagra No. 48
Open daily, 14.00 - 22.00 (Weekday) / 10.00 - 22.00 (Weekend)

Udah lama nggak main ke @shuffle.id, Ms. Mimin kaget liat tumpukan board game yang makin banyak. Sekarang koleksi gamenya ada lebih dari 100 judul dan kalo mau main, cuma perlu bayar Rp 20.000/orang buat seharian! Wih, bisa jadi solusi kalo lagi bokek tapi pengen tetep hore-hore sama temen-temen sih ini.

Bakal ada coach yang siap nemenin kalo pengen tanya-tanya soal gamenya sekaligus ngajarin cara main. Mau cari game yang heboh sampe yang serius juga ada. Bisa nemenin juga lho kalo kamu kesepian, eh maksudnya kurang pemain. Sambil nemenin main, bisa pesen makanan, mulai dari snack kayak Cireng buat dimakan bareng sampe makanan berat kayak Ayam Rempah + Mashed Potato atau Indomie Kari.

Selain bisa main board game, kamu bisa beli board gamenya di @shuffle.id juga. Siapa tau mau modusin kecengan buat main bareng board game!

VERDICT: Walaupun bokek, yang penting tetep bisa hore-hore.

Leaving camp last week after a restful night over the surf..

End of day over the Utah desert.. A short climb away from the crowds taking in the view from Island In The Sky. Majestic views have so much power when you only share them with a small group of friends..

Never had I thought that one day I'd be bending over a patch of wild flowers photographing them. Seeing the yellow of the flowers and the blue from the ocean compliment each other so well I felt compelled to run towards it. Knowing that they will be gone in a few weeks only added to the feeling..
Downtime in Big Sur..

Somewhere along the Pacific Coast, on the way to Big Sur. Since the coastal road connecting SF to LA is closed in a few sections do to mudslides, we've enjoyed an unusually quiet stay here. I've actually never seen it so deserted. And it seems like the road won't open for a few months so take a trip down PCH if you have the time.. There will be some detours but you'll remember it even more.. Ps. Do you see the Bixby Bridge poking out?

Working on my pre-sleep routine in the Eastern Sierras. On a cold night (typically the ones with no clouds), I  fill up a water bottle with boiling hot water that I'll take to bed with me. I'll keep it at my feet for maximum comfort #üî•#‚õ∫Ô∏è

It takes a special person to be game for a 5:00 am sunrise ride. @jlawberry is one of them.. She took me to her favourite trail in the hills above Bishop. This image, shot before the sun rose, is my favourite form that morning. It's always about these "in between" moments..
It feels me with joy seeing how much snow there is in the upper parts of California. Surely a relief from the long drought..

Morgan working his way up the Saigon Boulder near Bishop, California. I have loved every second spent here. It's easy to love a place where the snowcapped peaks meet the desert. Ps. Morgan did get higher up the boulder but It's bit always about sharing the most impressive moments of the day.
The lower part of Mount Humphreys came out of the weather for a few seconds. I shot this frame, took my eyes off the viewfinder and watched it fade into the clouds once again..
A day at the Eureka Dunes, Death Valley. Happy to be in the desert again..

Early this morning in the Eastern Sierras..

Yesterday while on a date with my husband, I got hit with one of the worst migraines of my life. Since we weren't home, I couldn't do my little migraine hacks during the first 15 min of the visual aura (if you are familiar with migraines there is a window of 15 min where you see flashing lights and go partially blind before you get the migraine) so it was the first time in awhile I've actually had a full blown migraine. 
_

Not to be dramatic, but I thought my brain was swelling to the point I might actually die. For 5 hours I laid in a dark room and tried my best to sleep it off but who can sleep with that much pain? I couldn't post for #effectivehandstands which I have never missed posting for one of my challenges before but really, I didn't think anyone would care. 
_

Today, I'm in the "migraine hangover" stage as I call it where I have a bad headache, eyes are swollen, and I feel like I got hit by a truck. I have to figure out a way to stop these migraines because I can't live this way. 
_

So, before you give me all your suggestions just know that I've tried them ALL. I'm the kind of person that will try anything anyone tells me if it means I don't have to endure this pain anymore. Really though, right now I'm feeling so down and depressed about it because nothing has worked. 
_
If you get migraines or know anything that maybe has worked for others feel free to leave me a comment. üôèüèª Thank you for your continued love and support. I love you guys!

#migraine

My @Natgeo magazine cover story on Pope Francis and the Vatican is out! I spent a lot of time over the course of six months working on this project, with unprecedented access given to a photojournalist. On August 4 a beautiful photography book on this work on the Vatican, with great writing by Robert Draper, will be published by National Geographic, called 'Pope Francis and the New Vatican,‚Äô available for preorder and easy to find on Amazon right now. I‚Äôll be posting a few outtakes in the coming days. And stay tuned, in October @Natgeo magazine publish a story I shot in unexplored jungle in Honduras where I went with a team to visit a lost city once inhabited by an ancient civilisation that were neighbours to the Maya. It‚Äôs been an interesting, lately!  Edited to add: I took this picture on Christmas Day when Pope Francis made an unexpected visit to the Sistine Chapel after speaking to the people in St. Peter's Square from the balcony of the basilica. It was a wonderful Christmas present, to say the least.

A member of the Swiss Guard paces at his post near the foot of Scala Regia, the royal staircase that connects the Apostolic Palace to St. Peter‚Äôs Basilica in Vatican City. Once a formidable mercenary force dating back 500 years, the title Swiss Guard now usually refers to the Pontifical Swiss Guard, a small force of just over 100 Swiss Catholics who serve as bodyguards to the Pope. Despite their outwardly appearance of a ceremonial role, they are a serious and well-trained combat force, equipped with modern weaponry such as submachine guns. This is an outtake from my August @natgeo magazine cover story on Pope Francis and the Vatican. A National Geographic book from the assignment will also be published on August 4. #swissguard #vatican #thephotosociety
Villa Taverna, Rome, this morning.

On assignment for National Geographic Magazine at the Vatican this morning‚ÄîPope Francis is presented with a jersey in his name at a general audience. Before and after the audiences, held on Wednesdays in St. Peter‚Äôs Square, he spends considerable time meeting people who are sick, about to get married, or who just really want to meet him.

The largest-ever astronomical project, ALMA, is a cooperation between the three continents--North America, Europe, and East Asia--to build and network 66 radio antennas at 16,500 feet altitude in the Atacama Desert in Chile. The radio telescope array is searching the heavens for clues about the origins of the Universe and many other mysteries. This picture was shot on assignment for National Geographic Magazine, for a story that will be running in the April issue. #atacama #chile #ALMA @thephotosociety

An outtake from my upcoming story in the April issue of @natgeo Magazine on the ALMA radio telescope array in Chile. In this shot, workers prepare to put reflective panels on a European-built antenna.

And ALMA radio telescope array built by NRAO scans the heavens for traces of the Big Bang at 17K feet altitude in the high Atacama desert in Chile. Shot on assignment for @natgeo Magazine for a story appearing in the April edition of the magazine. #thephotosociety #chile #atacama #nrao #alma
Another outtake from my Brunelleschi Cupola story in the February issue of @natgeo magazine

Another outtake from my story on the Brunelleschi Cupola in the February issue of @natgeo Magazine. This was shot at dusk from the tower of the Palazzo Vecchio in Florence. #latergram #florence @natgeo @thephotosociety

An outtake from a National Geographic story on the Brunelleschi Cupola in Florence to be published in next month's issue, written by my good friend Tom Mueller. Please check out the magazine, and particularly the iPad edition of the magazine--it's just great.
Cinque Terre; an image that didn't run from a recent travel story on the Ligurian coastline. Goodby summer.

A laser scanner measures to millimeter precision the inner space of the Hall of 500 in The Palazzo Vecchio in Florence. This SLR photo was taken with about a half-hour exposure, only street lights from far below lighting the interior as the tiny green dot of laser furiously raced up and down the wall. Shot during a long project i undertook on the search for Leonardo da Vinci's lost painting "The Battle of Anghiari." Some scholars believe the painting may still survive behind the Giorgio Vasari frescos now covering the walls. The search for the painting is either dead or in deep hibernation, depending on who you ask, and we may never know whether any part of it survives. #latergram #thephotosociety

My fav coconut water brand @purecocobella now does vegan coconut yoghurt üëÖ and I'm obsessed! So much so that I've created a recipe for these little vegan frozen yog pops with crunchy choc-nola

Recipe: (makes 4)
1/4 cup @purecocobella yog 
1/2 cup dragonfruit or berries
2 tbsp peanut butter
2 medjool date (pitted)
1/4 cup chocolate granola (store bought or homemade- ps. I have a recipe in my ebook) 
1 tbsp coconut flakes
2 tsp cacao nibs 
How to make:
1. Add the dragonfruit/berries, peanut butter, dates and half of the coconut yogurt to a blender, blend smooth. 
2. Sprinkle the granola, coconut and nibs in the popsicle moulds and pour over the mixture, spoon the rest of the coconut yogurt over and give it a little swirl with a popsicle stick.
3. Place in the freezer to set overnight. 
4. Eat straight from the freezer! 
Optional yummy extra: you may like to melt down dark chocolate and pour a couple of teaspoons over the set pops and sprinkle with extra granola, coconut and nibs. 
I use silicone popsicle moulds which I found on eBay üôà

Like so many, I grew up reading National Geographic, watching wild life shows and being completely fascinated with our natural world. These media outlets planted a seed in me at an early age, a desire to want to see these places first hand. The #Kalahari was one of those areas and it's been a dream come true to finally experience it. Tonight we finished up yet another incredible day here in a quite meadow at twilight, telling stories about the day and watching the stars slowly take over the night sky. This was the last photo I shot, a #camelThornTree surrounded by lush grass during the tail end of the rainy season. So here goes nothing... Recently I've been in a bit of a creative rut with my photography/Instagram and not feeling very motivated to post. This makes me super sad as photography is my first love and has always made me so happy. I think I've been putting too much pressure on posting and definitely haven't been enjoying this. So... I've decided to change it up a bit and go back to my roots of Instagram and just post what I want to post, if I like it, I'll post it. I feel like I've got my photo mojo back on my trip to NYC and Miami. I've been really excited about shooting and I'm SO excited to actually share it with you guys. Anyway, sorry for the crazy long speech, I just wanted to let you know how I was feeling and that I'm going to be mashing down the photography game again! Thanks so much to all of you who follow me and take time to like and comment on my images, it means a lot! Here's to the next chapter üôèüèª P.S. Say hello to some white borders

Panna Meena Ka Kund,  is an eight storey step well located on the Jaipur-Amer road. Built in the 16th century, the sight storey well has criss-cross steps arranged on three sides with small niches created into the walls. Not only did the step well served as a source of water, it was also the place of community gathering where people would come to chat. Back home after a month in Iran and Portugal and thrilled to find this in the mail! My latest story in National Geographic magazine. Pinch me it‚Äôs a dream. Shot alongside my family in Pakistan‚Äôs Karakoram mountains (with the tiny Fujifilm #x100t), it was initially an online only feature, but it ended up as well in the magazine... with my text! This is the part that I personally find hard to believe. I have renewed my admiration for writers... what a perilous job it is to juggle words. For the real thing, get a copy of the magazine (April 2017) or see the link in my Instagram profile.

Pakistan, Gojal region, Karakoram mountains. Young Wakhis dance after celebrating Imamat Day, the yearly celebration that marks the anniversary of the day that their present (or Hazir) Imam succeeded his predecessor. These young men study in big cities away from these mountains, and for them, this celebration is also an important time to relink to their homeland. The girls were playing volleyball nearby. Part of an upcoming @natgeo story coming in April in the magazine. Thanks always to @sajjidalvi for his help out there! @natgeocreative

Look out for this April issue of National Geographic magazine with my story on Pakistan's Karakoram mountains. Here, at a school in the village of Zood Khun, girls play an intense game of cricket during a break. Behind them, a high-altitude trail leads into the Pamir Mountains of Afghanistan. It's an amazing region, very happy to be able to share it. Meanwhile I am off to Iran, to the desert and onward surfing in Portugal. Packing confusion. #girlpower @natgeocreative
"And what‚Äôs behind that one?‚Äù Timot√© and iluka and the Taklamakan desert. Xinjiang, China. #sonsofthedesert @paleyography  @natgeocreative

Back home after a fantastic time in Pakistan. I will be unearthing some mountain power in the next couple of days, before I am off to Iran.
The Pamir/Hindukush/Karakoram mountains regions (part of the greater Western Himalayas) in Afghanistan/Pakistan/Tajikistan have been my longest obsession as a photographer. I started ‚Äúworking‚Äù there back in 1999/2000, unknowing of where I was going - my beard got white over there and I have happily explored most corners of that region - but then soon enough need to return.
This here is a Wakhi household in the lower elevation of the Afghan Pamir; some hectic before food and a young woman showing her ring. My tripod was a plastic drum laying around the kitchen, shot on a Contax 645. In Wakhi language, each part of the house has a specific word for it. This here is by the Dildung - the open hearth. @natgeocreative
Back in Pakistan for a bit - incredible, often misunderstood. Follow me on my Story on Instagram as I roam Lahore day and night, one of my favorite city in Asia! @natgeocreative

Back from Nepal and thrilled to announce that one of my image has won a World Press award! It was shot last June, part of a National Geographic story on crossing China by train (link in my profile). The winning image was posted here on Sept 2nd: the legs of a woman carrying 50 Yuan in her leggings. Here is another one from that story, Uyghur women at the Yarkand train station. I will keep sharing less exposed corner or the world here on my feed, thanks for following! #uyghur #xinjiang #yarkand #worldpressphoto @natgeocreative

She woke up from a nap, already the phone in her hand. The daughter of the border guard at the check post into lower Mustang. Outside, a wide valley lead over a high pass into China. #Nepal #mustang @geomagazin
Chai stop ain't bad. On the way to Beni, start of the Annapurna circuit. #nepal @geomagazin
Kathmandu cowboy party was Saturday.  @voguemagazine
Kathmandu here I come! @voguemagazine

Family members holding portraits of their relatives in the Pamir. These hand painted black and white photographs were done mostly in the 80‚Äôs by itinerant photographers going to mountain villages - often on foot. I would love to know more about these travellers, but information is hard to find. Part of my collection of photographs of soviet era family albums and portraits. #sovietera #tajikistan #handpainted
Tajik policeman #3: the Vrang policeman sharing his family photo album. I have a nice collection of such soviet beauties. What does it say at the bottom right? #collage

Tajik policeman #2: There is only one of them in Vrang. I was watching the Pyanj river, Afghanistan in the distance, minding my own business. He stared. I spoke Wakhi to him then we really hit it off. I was first paraded into the police station, then fed candy and flat bread - no interrogation that day, I fed him a feeling of power. @natgeocreative #policeman

Tajik Policeman #1: Bored in Khorog. From a short series on policemen in Tajikistan. Please add melancholic accordion in background + cold smell of cigarettes and cheap vodka. Thanks. #policeman #pamir @natgeocreative

My other passion - kitesurfing‚Ä¶ or actually anything that glides on water. I wanted to be a pro windsurfer when I was a teenager, now I am just a photographer who kites when the wind is right. Being on water empties my head, reboot, rejuvenate. The ocean, it makes me less of a pain to others. Nature's work! Last week end, here at home on the Turkish Aegean. #kitesurfing #kitesurfingworld #viewfromthepilot @natgeocreative

Endangered Laos warty newts at the @rivermuseum in Dubuque, Iowa. 
This species lives only in the Northern mountainous areas of Laos. They are mostly aquatic and thrive in streams and pools at high elevations. The main threat to this species is collection and exportation into the international pet trade in Germany and Japan. Since these animals have brightly colored markings and are active during the day, they aren‚Äôt difficult to locate and it‚Äôs possible for collectors to spot and grab up each and every mature individual to be taken from one site in just a few days, wiping out a local population. Since such a large number can be taken at once, they are often sold in large groups by the kilogram. The Laos warty newt was listed in 2008 as a Category I species in the Lao WIldlife and Aquatic Law, which means all commercial trade of this species is prohibited. So, some protection is possible at least, given proper law enforcement.
.
.
#laos #laoswartynewts #newt #rare #rareanimals #notapet #wildlife #wildlifephotography #photoark #natgeo

A critically endangered red ruffed lemur at the Plzen Zoo in the Czech Rebublic. These lemurs are very clean and spend a large amount of time grooming themselves with their specialized incisor teeth, hind claws, and tongues- which are colored black. They live in matriarchal groups and forage for food together during the abundant wet season. Unlike most lemurs, red ruffed lemurs will often divide and find food on their own during the dry season. 
Red ruffed lemurs live in a very small range in the forests of northern Madagascar and are threatened by the huge surge of illegal rosewood logging that began after an undemocratic change in political power in the area in 2009. These lemurs are also threatened by hunting, burning of habitat, the illegal pet trade, and frequent cyclones.
To see a full length image of a red ruffed lemur check out @natgeo!
.
.
#redruffedlemur #lemurs #cuteanimals #notapet #wildlifephotography #wildlife #photoark #natgeo

These Arctic ground squirrels at the University of Alaska at Fairbanks are sleeping so soundly that, when handled, it takes them three hours just to wake up. Indeed, they are grand champion hibernators, sleeping up to seven months a year or more. "You could put people into hibernation for space trips if you could understand it better," said Franziska 'Fran' Kohl, one of the biologists here. "They also show symptoms of Alzheimer's during hibernation."
This cold-weather rodent is also the only mammal that can drop its body temperature to below freezing. Most impressively, it can completely heal traumatic brain injuries while hibernating. Biologists at UAF have been studying this species for more than 20 years, but many mysteries still remain.
.
.

A derbyana flower beetle at the @stlzoo.

An American Alligator at the @KansasCityZoo. 
Saved from the verge of extinction, these behemoth reptiles of the southern wetlands now thrive in increasing numbers (over 1,000,000). Restrictions on the hide trade and habitat preservation measures have kept the alligator, a survivor of some 180 to 200 million years, alive and well. 
It is no exaggeration to say that saving the biodiversity of Earth is now a matter of life and death for all of us. The vibrancy of plant and animal life, from the tropical forests to the seas, is what sustains us. We must have a healthy planet to stay healthy ourselves. The good news is that we can and will save the things we care most about. This species proves just that.
To see a video of this alligator, check out @natgeo!

A critically endangered Singapore crab at Singapore Zoo. 
This crab is threatened mainly by water pollution and loss of forest cover. Acidification of the streams they live in as well as the lowering water table have contributed to the decline of this species. Thankfully, Bukit Timah Hill and the associated stream systems in Jungle Fall Valley continue to be conserved and studied in efforts to maintain the populations of many species there, including the Singapore crab. The Singapore Zoo is leading the effort with a captive breeding program to help save the species as well.
To see a video of this crab, check out @natgeo!

A beaded gecko at @cfisheries in Tennessee. 
Beaded geckos can be found in dry, arid parts of Australia. Like most small lizards, their diet consists mainly of insects. Tiny, fine teeth line their jaws, however geckos will either crush their prey or simply swallow it whole as opposed to chewing it.

A critically endangered male Eastern bongo at the @greatplainszoo. 
Bongos are the largest of all African forest antelope species. They are distinguishable by their reddish coat with white stripes and long spiraled antlers. Bongos are the only spiraled-horned antelope species in which both sexes have horns. This subspecies can be found in mountainous regions of Kenya, but unfortunately their numbers are drastically declining due to increased hunting, disease, and habitat loss to illegal logging. Today, less than 140 Eastern bongos exist in the wild. .

The Torre De Lamberti, Verona Italy üáÆüáπ
üîπüîπüîπ
The Torre dei Lamberti is a 84 m high tower in Verona, northern Italy.
üî∏üî∏üî∏
Construction of the tower was started in 1172. In May 1403 the top of the tower was struck by lightning, but the restoration works didn't start until 1448 and took 16 years. During that time, the tower was enlarged: The more recent sections can be recognized today by the use of different materials (such as marble). The large clock was added in 1779.
üîπüîπüîπ
The tower has two bells: the Marangona signals fires, work times, and the hours of the day, while the largest, called Rengo, is used to call the population to arms or to invoke the city's councils.

Beauty moment in Japan! This new ritual is pretty cool, simple and beautiful. Here are the lotions I'm using right now, as well as the face wash, all @shiseido - I love the day cream because it has a very potent anti-aging action but also a sunscreen to save my skin now that I am living under the sun in LA and that I keep on forgetting my hat.
Also the ceramic tools I was telling you about earlier, all hand made, pretty holistic and amazing. Discover the line at link in bio. #FutureSolutionLX #GaranceinJapan #sponsored
Beauty. Danjogaran in Koyasan. #garanceinjapan #FutureSolutionLX @shiseido

The reason the team at @shiseido took me on this journey was to make me discover the feeling of Japanese beauty and care, and it really culminated with the crazy 90mn facial I had. If you're like me and love skin care and massages and facials (I'm an addict), read on: the Yutaka facial, which accompanies the #FutureSolutionLX line, is a multi-sensory experience and revolves around one plant. A special room scent comes with it, as well as a special soundtrack that was recorded specifically for this and mixed with sounds of nature captured in Japan, and special hand made ceramic tools (a ceramic hot stone for your stomach, and two hot massage "mushrooms" for you face) - it's so trippy and Japanese and amazing. I got a hot spring bath after that and I thought I was in heaven. 
My skin too. 
Ok and now a little end of the super long story secret to thank you for reading on. Did you know that you can go to most Shiseido parlors and get a free facial? You just have to ask. I know it sounds crazy, but I verified and it's true. It's been going on for years and is just like a hidden secret. So I'm just sayin. (This specific massage I was talking to you about won't hit the spas until the fall, but other ones, yes!!!) #garanceinjapan #sponsored

Sleeping in a shukubo tonight in a monastery, Henjoson-in - the futons are unrolled on the floor before going to sleep. Diner at 6pm, curfew at 10pm, meditation at 6am, breakfast at 7am. Loving every second of it (which is easy to say when you're jet lagged and go to bed at 9 and wake up at 4 anyway) - what an experience!!! Thank you so much @shiseido - living one of my dreams! #futuresolutionlx #garanceinjapan
In Mount Koya, happy after a guided meditation by Nobu, a Buddhist monk - check the stories for more üôèüèº photo @yingchunyc @shiseido #futuresolutionlx #garanceinjapan

I discovered the magic of onsen (hot springs) for the first time here, in the Ago Bay, and I can't tell you how wonderful it is. The second we step foot in the bath, @em_note and I were like "what is that?" It's like all our stress, jet lag, tensions left our bodies in a second. Oh, also. Even though I love me @calarenasummerwear swimsuit (Corsican brand!!!) - It's 100% better naked. Ok, off to yoga #mostbeautifyingtripever #garanceinjapan #futuresolutionlx @shiseido

This week I'm escaping normal life and stepping into the beautiful world of @shiseido for a journey to Japan. And tonight I was able to see the most beautiful sunset over Tokyo - as I was taking a bath. Doesn't happen everyday. The dream!!! #futuresolutionlx #garanceinjapan

When we are looking to isolate only one muscle group throughout the exercise "lifting heavy" isn‚Äôt really possible compared to your normal compound movements but we have other advantages:
-
‚Ä¢ providing more volume when secondary muscles are tired and we are not able to lift heavy anymore
‚Ä¢ targeting muscles that we want to focus on, without training another
‚Ä¢ working on the primary muscle group without overdeveloping secondary
‚Ä¢ pre-exhausting underdeveloped area.
-
After few heavy sets of any compound movement usually our stabilizers or any other secondary muscles involved in exercise are too tired to lift heavy any more. However the major muscle group that we train isn‚Äôt exhausted yet. Our objective is to incorporate as many muscles fibers as possible and train them to the point when they can‚Äôt do any more work. So this is a perfect time when we can use isolation exercise in our routine and do few more sets to deplete the rest of the energy (glycogen) from our muscles and train them to the extreme.
